Five Truths About Terrorism
SAO PAULO – American policy is being held hostage by terrorism.
In December 2015, polls indicated that one in six Americans, or about 16% of the population, now ranked terrorism as the top problem facing the country—an increase of 3% in a month.
For ten years, never had so many Americans been so concerned about terrorism, even though their number is still far below the 46% recorded in the days following the September 11, 2001 attacks.
The consequences of this evolution in public opinion were especially felt during the Republican primary for the presidential election.
Donald Trump's candidacy, whose anti-Muslim rhetoric is particularly fiery (if not incendiary), has undoubtedly benefited from it.
Some politicians feel authorized to speak of the battle against terrorism as the "Third World War."
Terrorism is a problem for the United States, as shown by the San Bernardino attack in California in December of last year.
But the presidential candidates, like certain media outlets that favor the old adage "if it bleeds, it leads," have exaggerated the proportions.
To place terrorism in its true perspective, Americans – like others – should keep the following considerations in mind:
Terrorism is a kind of theater.
Terrorists are more concerned with grabbing attention and dominating the political news than with the actual number of their victims.
The Islamic State (IS) takes great care with its staging.
The barbaric beheadings broadcast on social networks are intended to destabilize and outrage – and therefore to monopolize attention.
Exaggerating their consequences and making big headlines out of every terrorist act is playing into the terrorists' game.
Terrorism is not the most serious threat facing the populations of developed countries.
Terrorism kills far fewer people than road accidents or smoking.
From this perspective, terrorism is not even a real threat — neither major nor minor.
You are more likely to be struck by lightning than to be killed by a terrorist.
According to experts, the probability that an American citizen is assassinated by a terrorist is one in 3.5 million.
Americans face a greater risk of dying in their bathtub (1 in 950,000), from an accident caused by a household appliance (1 in 1.5 million), from a deer or elk crossing the road (1 in 2 million), or in a commercial airplane crash (1 in 2.9 million).
Six thousand Americans die every year while driving, texting or talking on their cell phones.
It is several hundred times the number of those who die from terrorism.
Radical Islamic terrorism kills fewer Americans than attacks carried out by disgruntled employees or mass shootings at universities or schools.
Terrorism is not the Third World War.
Global terrorism is not new.
It often takes a generation to quell a terrorist outbreak.
At the beginning of the 20th century, the anarchist movement killed a number of heads of state in the name of utopian ideals.
During the 1960s and 1970s, the Red Brigades and the Red Army Faction, originating from the "autonomous" left, diverted airplanes out of national borders and kidnapped or killed business executives or political leaders (as well as ordinary citizens).
Today's jihadist extremists are an old political phenomenon dressed in religious clothing.
Many of their leaders are not traditional fundamentalists, but individuals whose identities have been shattered by globalization, seeking meaning in the imaginary and pure community of an Islamic caliphate.
It will take time and effort to defeat them, but the restrictive nature of EI limits its scope of attraction.
His sectarian attacks already prevent him from addressing all Muslims, let alone Hindus, Christians, or other believers.
IS will ultimately be defeated, just as the transnational terrorist groups that preceded it have been.
Terrorism is like jiu-jitsu.
The weaker of the two adversaries uses the strength of the stronger to defeat him.
No terrorist organization has the power of a state, and few terrorist movements have managed to overthrow one.
But if they succeed in shocking and provoking citizens of a state enough to drive them to futile actions, they may hope to gain the advantage.
In 2001, Al-Qaeda succeeded in drawing the Americans into Afghanistan.
ISIS was born from the ruins of the US-led invasion of Iraq, which followed the intervention in Afghanistan.
To defeat terrorism, it takes smart power.
A smart power is capable of combining the coercive power (hard power) of the army and police with the power of influence (soft power) of seduction and persuasion.
Power and influence are also necessary if one wants to vaccinate those on the periphery who the irreducible are trying to recruit.
This is why the attention given to the narrative of events and how the actions of the United States are commented on social media is just as important and necessary as precision airstrikes.
The rhetoric of confrontation, which points fingers at Muslims and alienates the goodwill that could help us obtain crucial information, puts us all in danger.
Reason why the anti-Islam stance of some of the current presidential candidates is so counterproductive.
The terrorist issue is serious, and it deserves to be placed among the priorities of our intelligence and police services, our armed forces, and our diplomacy.
It constitutes an important element of our foreign policy.
And it is essential to keep weapons of mass destruction out of the reach of terrorists.
But we must not fall into the trap set by the terrorists.
Let us not fill the theater where the actions carried out by thugs and hooligans take place.
If we abandon them the grand stage of our public speech, we will diminish the quality of our civic life and misalign our priorities.
Our strength would then be used against us.
